snippet.textDisplay:
THE SONG IS SUCH A PIECE OF ART!!😭❤
Here are my observations from my first few listens. (Sorry, I'll be the paragraph guy)

-The whole song and the video is from the perspectives of a girl who has stepped into her adulthood.  And we can observe it from the video and the lyrics that she's a middle class child born in a society where it is believed that a girl child can only be a good homemaker in her adulthood. 



First, let's start with the Video.📹

In the beginning of the video, we see Square and Mohito sitting on a bench, folding hair ribbons with their fingers. It's a rural sight. Then we see Mohito and Square walking off the bench.
-Notice, Square here leaves the ribbon behind on the bench whereas Mohito takes it away with himself. This could signify that Mohito will show us the childhood character (memories she's been carrying) and Square is gonna show us the present adult character. And that's exactly what happens. (Note the ribbon, it plays a significant part in the whole video)

MC Square has walked into a dark, much urban looking room/studio where he starts his verse.
Let's check the lyrics✒
-He's saying that he also had two options infront of him like Robert Frost. Robert Frost is a famous nature poet. Frost has got a poem named, 'The Road Not Taken' where he talks about the dilemma he faced while choosing his path as a poet. Frost said that he had two roads infront of his, and the both weren't very popular. So square refers to that here.
-"Aur main aadam jaat", remember the word aadam. Here he says that he's a human being.
-"Chal diya seb khaan khattar". Adam and Eve reference where the devil offered Adam a forbidden fruit(an apple). Adam sounds like Aadam, and it is believed in Christianity that all the human beings are offspring of Adam and Eve. POWERFUL PENGAME!!✒💪

-He also says that she(the main character) left behind the mulberries, referring to the childhood innocence, that's what I'm guessing.

Now let's come back to the video.📹

We see the apples in Square's room, and the mulberry tree can be seen through the window.
-Now that's when Mohito enters, he enters the scene where there is the mulberry tree (rural area again)
-He talks about her childhood memories, and the moment he completes his part, he throws away the ribbon, note again.
-Now MC Square enters again, he catches the ribbon from that room where we can see urban traces.
-Awards hanging on the walls shows that she has achieved a lot in her life, and to the contrary, the lyrics are talking about what all she lost, talking about her reminiscent past.
-Now square enters where Mohito was sitting, and DAMNNNN🤯
You see, Square was talking about "Jawaani", and yes, he was pointing at mohito. Jawaani is the phase between one's childhood and adulthood. That's where they both meet and we call that the adolescent age. Too good to be a coincidence, isn't it?🤔

Now, Square enters another room in the rural area, and inside the room the girl is telling herself things like "you're sitting inside the room reminiscing about your past, mourning about the lost childhood."

Again we see Mohito resting in a traditional Indian rural bed with writings and drawings on the floor and talking about her childhood.

Now Square finally finds her childhood (in her memories) and finally they both start to get the connection.

Basically Square/the adult girl has learnt to accept that her childhood would never return and she has to live on with her memories now.
-Square comes and sits on the bench while the ribbon is no longer in his hand (it's on the bench)
Now none of them are holding the ribbon, now she has completely given up on her past.
-Mohito's verse here signifies that the girl has already crossed two phases of her life and now she has finally decided to do something on her own now
-That's when the neighbours say... "Chhori sivasin holi.. Byaa do"
And that's where they reunite again on the bench where they started.



This was my observation from the first listen/watch. Continue with your opinions in the replies. 👇🏻
Pardon me if I've got something wrong, I've got a loose grip in Haryanvi, so I must have missed a lot. I wish I could understand the Lang 😢❤

Cheers to this masterpiece!! W the whole team🥂🔥

snippet.textDisplay: Although a Maharashtrian, but I loved the song. Especially the ending, it ended on a freaking reality check. As Indians, we love our country, but there are still these elements of concern like child marriages which do exist (With all due respect to Haryana). Happy to see Haryana developing and such amazing artists taking the initiative to address such an issue via Coke Studio. The hook line is stuck in my head. Rehya bachpan bhola kitta.. OMG.. awesome work.. Kudos to everyone who is involved in the making of this gem..❤️😍
